Summer Streets is an annual car-free event held in August. This year,  the event takes place on August 7th and 14th, 7 AM-1 PM in Manhattan between the Brooklyn Bridge and Central Park. Nearly seven miles of NYC’s streets are open for people to play, run, walk, and bike along Park Avenue and its connecting streets. This video was filmed yesterday during my walk on Park Avenue from 34th Street to 47th Street in Midtown Manhattan. @nyc_dot 

Full video in my YouTube channel “NYC loves NYC”

“Postcards” is the Staten Island September 11 Memorial, a beautiful remembrance of the lives lost. Resembling a pair of wings reaching skyward, it sits right on the shore of Staten Island with a clear view of the World Trade Center site.

These are the the highlights of my walk in The Ramble yesterday.  You can watch the full video in my YouTube channel (NYC loves NYC). 

Tag someone you’d like to explore this Central Park oasis with.

“The Ramble is the most well-known of Central Park’s woodland landscapes, which offer visitors an experience of the woods in the center of New York City. Its 36 acres were designed to look like the forests of upstate New York and include winding paths and trails, rustic bridges, a meandering stream, dramatic rock outcroppings, and dense plantings. The design of the Ramble was intentionally intricate, with twisting paths that encourage wandering and create a sense of mystery and surprise, but also make it challenging to navigate.”
https://www.centralparknyc.org/locations/the-ramble

📍The Ramble, Mid-Park between 73rd and 79th Streets, Central Park, Manhattan, New York City

The 30,000 sq. ft. iconic Times Square digital spectacular known as "Big Kahuna" has a new media art execution titled WHALE No. 2 by @dstrictholdings 
Illuminating the pedestrian plaza, the public media art display transforms the huge screen into a hyper-realistic, undulating ocean environment occupied by an enormous blue whale. The whale is made of water and moves freely and harmoniously among the waves.

Now through July 26. One-minute display every half hour starting at 12 p.m. each day and ending at midnight. By Silvercast Media

📍 Broadway from 45th Street to 46th Street, Times Square, New York City

node.text:
New York City threw a ticker-tape parade earlier today to say thank you to the essential workers who helped the city through the COVID-19 pandemic. The Hometown Heroes Parade took place along a stretch of downtown Manhattan known as the Canyon of Heroes, which has hosted parades for over a century. The Canyon of Heroes is the name for the over 200 black granite plaques that commemorate and list every single ticker tape parade in New York City history. The plaques are embedded in the sidewalks along Broadway in Lower Manhattan. They run on both sides of the street, from the beginning of Broadway at Battery Place, all the way north to Chambers Street, right next to City Hall.

The term ticker-tape parade originated in New York City after a spontaneous celebration held on October 28, 1886, during the dedication of the Statue of Liberty and is still most closely associated with New York City. The term ticker-tape originally referred to the use of the paper output of ticker tape machines, which were remotely driven devices used in brokerages to provide updated stock market quotes. The term ticker came from the sound made by the machine as it printed. The used paper from the ticker tape machines were used for celebratory parades in New York City. 

📍Canyon of Heroes (Broadway from Battery Place to Chambers Street in the Financial District), Lower Manhattan, New York City

In the knick of time

Tag your friends you’d like to go to this beautiful rooftop bar with. 

The thirteenth through fifteenth stories of the Knickerbocker Hotel are part of the mansard roof, which is clad in green copper. On top is the St. Cloud Rooftop Bar. Named for the late-19th century hotel that originally occupied the site, St. Cloud Rooftop is a New York rooftop bar located at the five star Knickerbocker Hotel, just off Times Square. From the terrace you get a lovely view of all the skyscrapers. There are both seatings indoors and outdoors. 

📍St. Cloud Rooftop, 6 Times Square 17th Floor, Manhattan, New York City
